# Cache Groups Cleanup Cron Configuration
# 
# This file contains example cron entries for running cache groups cleanup.
# Copy the desired entries to your crontab or to /etc/cron.d/cache-groups-cleanup
#
# To install:
# 1. Copy this file: sudo cp cache_groups_cron.example /etc/cron.d/cache-groups-cleanup
# 2. Remove the .example extension and edit paths as needed
# 3. Ensure the file has proper permissions: sudo chmod 644 /etc/cron.d/cache-groups-cleanup

# Run cleanup every hour (recommended for most setups)
0 * * * * root /opt/cache_groups/run_cleanup.sh >/dev/null 2>&1

# Run cleanup every 30 minutes with 2-hour retention
*/30 * * * * root /opt/cache_groups/run_cleanup.sh --max-age 7200 >/dev/null 2>&1

# Run cleanup every 15 minutes with verbose logging (for debugging)
# */15 * * * * root /opt/cache_groups/run_cleanup.sh --verbose

# Run cleanup daily at 2 AM with 24-hour retention (for low-traffic sites)
# 0 2 * * * root /opt/cache_groups/run_cleanup.sh --max-age 86400

# Run cleanup every 6 hours with custom Redis socket path
# 0 */6 * * * root /opt/cache_groups/run_cleanup.sh --socket-path /tmp/redis.sock

# Notes:
# - Adjust paths to match your installation directory
# - The 'root' user should be changed to the appropriate user (e.g., 'trafficserver')
# - Remove >/dev/null 2>&1 if you want to receive email notifications
# - Consider running cleanup more frequently for high-traffic sites
# - Less frequent cleanup is fine for sites with longer-lived content